"== 1 failed, 1 passed, 1 skipped, 1 xfailed, 1 xpassed, 1 error in 0.12s ==="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:456
msgid ""
"The :option:`-r` options accepts a number of characters after it, with ``a`` "
"used above meaning \"all except passes\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:459
msgid "Here is the full list of available characters that can be used:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:461
msgid "``f`` - failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:462
msgid "``E`` - error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:463
msgid "``s`` - skipped"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:464
msgid "``x`` - xfailed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:465
msgid "``X`` - xpassed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:466
msgid "``p`` - passed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:467
msgid "``P`` - passed with output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:469
msgid "Special characters for (de)selection of groups:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:471
msgid "``a`` - all except ``pP``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:472
msgid "``A`` - all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:473
msgid ""
"``N`` - none, this can be used to display nothing (since ``fE`` is the "
"default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:475
msgid ""
"More than one character can be used, so for example to only see failed and "
"skipped tests, you can execute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:477
msgid ""
"$ pytest -rfs\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-9.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"collected 6 items\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py .FEsxX                                               [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================== ERRORS "
"==================================\n"
"_______________________ ERROR at setup of test_error "
"_______________________\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.fixture\n"
"    def error_fixture():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________________ test_fail "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_fail():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_example.py::test_fail - assert 0\n"
"SKIPPED [1] test_example.py:22: skipping this test\n"
"== 1 failed, 1 passed, 1 skipped, 1 xfailed, 1 xpassed, 1 error in 0.12s ==="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:509
msgid ""
"Using ``p`` lists the passing tests, whilst ``P`` adds an extra section "
"\"PASSES\" with those tests that passed but had captured output:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:512
msgid ""
"$ pytest -rpP\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-9.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"collected 6 items\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py .FEsxX                                               [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================== ERRORS "
"==================================\n"
"_______________________ ERROR at setup of test_error "
"_______________________\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.fixture\n"
"    def error_fixture():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________________ test_fail "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_fail():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"================================== PASSES "
"==================================\n"
"_________________________________ test_ok "
"__________________________________\n"
"--------------------------- Captured stdout call "
"---------------------------\n"
"ok\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"PASSED test_example.py::test_ok\n"
"== 1 failed, 1 passed, 1 skipped, 1 xfailed, 1 xpassed, 1 error in 0.12s ==="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:549
msgid ""
"By default, parametrized variants of skipped tests are grouped together if "
"they share the same skip reason. You can use :option:`--no-fold-skipped` to "
"print each skipped test separately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:556
msgid "Modifying truncation limits"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:560
msgid ""
"Default truncation limits are 8 lines or 640 characters, whichever comes "
"first. To set custom truncation limits you can use the following "
"configuration file options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:565 ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:573
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"truncation_limit_lines = 10\n"
"truncation_limit_chars = 90"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:579
msgid ""
"That will cause pytest to truncate the assertions to 10 lines or 90 "
"characters, whichever comes first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:581
msgid ""
"Setting both :confval:`truncation_limit_lines` and :confval:"
"`truncation_limit_chars` to ``0`` will disable the truncation. However, "
"setting only one of those values will disable one truncation mode, but will "
"leave the other one intact."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:586
msgid "Creating JUnitXML format files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:588
msgid ""
"To create result files which can be read by Jenkins_ or other Continuous "
"integration servers, use this invocation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:591
msgid "pytest --junit-xml=path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:595
msgid "to create an XML file at ``path``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:599
msgid ""
"To set the name of the root test suite xml item, you can configure the "
"``junit_suite_name`` option in your config file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:603
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_suite_name = \"my_suite\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:610
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_suite_name = my_suite"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:617
msgid ""
"JUnit XML specification seems to indicate that ``\"time\"`` attribute should "
"report total test execution times, including setup and teardown (`1 <http://"
"windyroad.com.au/dl/Open%20Source/JUnit.xsd>`_, `2 <https://www.ibm.com/"
"support/knowledgecenter/en/SSQ2R2_14.1.0/com.ibm.rsar.analysis.codereview."
"cobol.doc/topics/cac_useresults_junit.html>`_). It is the default pytest "
"behavior. To report just call durations instead, configure the "
"``junit_duration_report`` option like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:626
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_duration_report = \"call\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:633
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_duration_report = call"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:641
msgid "record_property"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:643
msgid ""
"If you want to log additional information for a test, you can use the "
"``record_property`` fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:646
msgid ""
"def test_function(record_property):\n"
"    record_property(\"example_key\", 1)\n"
"    assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:652
msgid ""
"This will add an extra property ``example_key=\"1\"`` to the generated "
"``testcase`` tag:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:655
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"test_function\" file=\"test_function.py\" line=\"0\" "
"name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.0009\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"example_key\" value=\"1\" />\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:663
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can integrate this functionality with custom markers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:665
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_collection_modifyitems(session, config, items):\n"
"    for item in items:\n"
"        for marker in item.iter_markers(name=\"test_id\"):\n"
"            test_id = marker.args[0]\n"
"            item.user_properties.append((\"test_id\", test_id))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:676
msgid "And in your tests:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:678
msgid ""
"# content of test_function.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.test_id(1501)\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:688
msgid "Will result in:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:690
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"test_function\" file=\"test_function.py\" line=\"0\" "
"name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.0009\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"test_id\" value=\"1501\" />\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:700 ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:764
msgid ""
"Please note that using this feature will break schema verifications for the "
"latest JUnitXML schema. This might be a problem when used with some CI "
"servers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:705
msgid "record_xml_attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:707
msgid ""
"To add an additional xml attribute to a testcase element, you can use "
"``record_xml_attribute`` fixture. This can also be used to override existing "
"values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:710
msgid ""
"def test_function(record_xml_attribute):\n"
"    record_xml_attribute(\"assertions\", \"REQ-1234\")\n"
"    record_xml_attribute(\"classname\", \"custom_classname\")\n"
"    print(\"hello world\")\n"
"    assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:718
msgid ""
"Unlike ``record_property``, this will not add a new child element. Instead, "
"this will add an attribute ``assertions=\"REQ-1234\"`` inside the generated "
"``testcase`` tag and override the default ``classname`` with "
"``\"classname=custom_classname\"``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:722
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"custom_classname\" file=\"test_function.py\" "
"line=\"0\" name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.003\" assertions=\"REQ-1234\">\n"
"    <system-out>\n"
"        hello world\n"
"    </system-out>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:732
msgid ""
"``record_xml_attribute`` is an experimental feature, and its interface might "
"be replaced by something more powerful and general in future versions. The "
"functionality per-se will be kept, however."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:736
msgid ""
"Using this over ``record_xml_property`` can help when using ci tools to "
"parse the xml report. However, some parsers are quite strict about the "
"elements and attributes that are allowed. Many tools use an xsd schema (like "
"the example below) to validate incoming xml. Make sure you are using "
"attribute names that are allowed by your parser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:741
msgid "Below is the Scheme used by Jenkins to validate the XML report:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:743
msgid ""
"<xs:element name=\"testcase\">\n"
"    <xs:complexType>\n"
"        <xs:sequence>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"skipped\" minOccurs=\"0\" maxOccurs=\"1\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"error\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"failure\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"system-out\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"system-err\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"        </xs:sequence>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"name\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"required\"/>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"assertions\" type=\"xs:string\" "
"use=\"optional\"/>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"time\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"optional\"/>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"classname\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"optional\"/"
">\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"status\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"optional\"/>\n"
"    </xs:complexType>\n"
"</xs:element>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:770
msgid "record_testsuite_property"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:774
msgid ""
"If you want to add a properties node at the test-suite level, which may "
"contain properties that are relevant to all tests, you can use the "
"``record_testsuite_property`` session-scoped fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:777
msgid ""
"The ``record_testsuite_property`` session-scoped fixture can be used to add "
"properties relevant to all tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:780
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\", autouse=True)\n"
"def log_global_env_facts(record_testsuite_property):\n"
"    record_testsuite_property(\"ARCH\", \"PPC\")\n"
"    record_testsuite_property(\"STORAGE_TYPE\", \"CEPH\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class TestMe:\n"
"    def test_foo(self):\n"
"        assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:795
msgid ""
"The fixture is a callable which receives ``name`` and ``value`` of a "
"``<property>`` tag added at the test-suite level of the generated xml:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:798
msgid ""
"<testsuite errors=\"0\" failures=\"0\" name=\"pytest\" skipped=\"0\" "
"tests=\"1\" time=\"0.006\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"ARCH\" value=\"PPC\"/>\n"
"    <property name=\"STORAGE_TYPE\" value=\"CEPH\"/>\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"  <testcase classname=\"test_me.TestMe\" file=\"test_me.py\" line=\"16\" "
"name=\"test_foo\" time=\"0.000243663787842\"/>\n"
"</testsuite>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:808
msgid ""
"``name`` must be a string, ``value`` will be converted to a string and "
"properly xml-escaped."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:810
msgid ""
"The generated XML is compatible with the latest ``xunit`` standard, contrary "
"to `record_property`_ and `record_xml_attribute`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:815
msgid "Sending test report to an online pastebin service"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:817
msgid "**Creating a URL for each test failure**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:819
msgid "pytest --pastebin=failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:823
msgid ""
"This will submit test run information to a remote Paste service and provide "
"a URL for each failure.  You may select tests as usual or add for example :"
"option:`-x` if you only want to send one particular failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:827
msgid "**Creating a URL for a whole test session log**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:829
msgid "pytest --pastebin=all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:833
msgid ""
"Currently only pasting to the https://bpaste.net/ service is implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/output.rst:837
msgid ""
"If creating the URL fails for any reason, a warning is generated instead of "
"failing the entire test suite."
msgstr ""
